==English==

===Etymology===
From the Latin ''malitiosus'', from ''malitia'' meaning "malice", from ''malus'' meaning "bad"

===Adjective===
'''malicious''' (''no [[comparative]] or [[superlative]]'')

# The willful or will-less behavior of one who hurts others in a mean-spirited fashion.
# Total disrespect for all in regards to some sort of false bravado linked to "self-preservation".  
# Totally insane, mean-spirited ''evil'' way of dealing with all around you who care about your well being.
# Indulging or exercising [[malice]]; harboring ill will or enmity.  Acting upon mean-spirited choices regardless of will.
# Proceeding from hatred or ill will; dictated by malice; as, a malicious report; malicious mischief.
# (''law'') With wicked or mischievous intentions or motives; wrongful and done intentionally without just cause or excuse; as, a malicious act.

====Synonyms====
*(''indulging or exercising malice''): [[mischievous]], [[envious]], [[malevolent]], [[invidious]], [[spiteful]], [[bitter]], [[malignant]], [[rancorous]]


====Translations====

* French : [[malveillant]]
* [[Ido]] : mal-vol-anta, [[maligna]]

